\ul\b The History of CSS\ulnone\b0\par
In the following video, we will hear from Bert Bos, the co-creator of CSS, about how he and Hakon Lie developed CSS.\par
\par
Before CSS, the appearance of a Web page was dictated by HTML, which had very few visual styling tools, meaning most Web pages were looking simple.\par
\par
\b Before CSS\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 all documents looked very similar - it was difficult for different companies to express their brand identities in documents\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}possibilities for styling were very limited and style was difficult to control and maintain - style had to be applied to content directly, so we couldn't update style without having to touch content and vice versa.\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\b After CSS\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1\b0 Content authors didn't have to worry about style, they could just focus on content\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Content authors didn't have to worry about what device users would view their document on, those considerations could be handled by the CSS\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Style became much more efficient - a single rule could apply to multiple elements and a single style sheet could apply to multiple documents.\par

\pard\sl240\slmult1\par
\ul\b Definitions\ulnone\b0\par
CSS, or Cascading Style Sheets, is a style sheet language used to describe the way an HTML or XML document should look to a user. CSS us where you specify the color, size, spacing, font and other visual aspects of the content that we create in our markup language document.\par
\par
Most often we will see CSS used alongside HTML to describe a way a Web page looks and feels. We can have a Web page without CSS, but it would be very difficult to make it look the way we want with just HTML. This is why almost every Web page is a combination of HTML and CSS.\par
\par
\b CSS\b0\par
Stands for Cascading Style Sheets. A style sheet language for describing how to display an HTML document.\par
\par
\b HTML\b0\par
Stands for HyperText Markup Language, and it is the primary document format on the web. It is a standardized system for tagging content on a web page so that a web browser knows how to present it properly to the viewer. It is a standardized way to describe a document's structure and the roles of the different parts of that document.\par
\par
\b Web page\b0\par
A hypertext document connected to the World Wide Web\par
\par
\b Internet\b0\par
A global system of computer networks that connect to one another so that billions of different devices all over the world can share data. The internet is a collection of smaller networks that all combined create one large, all-inclusive global network.\par
\par
\b World Wide Web\b0\par
A collection of documents linked together by hypertext links, addressed using Uniform Resource Locators accessible on the Internet. The World Wide Web is an application of the internet.\par
\par
\b Web browser\b0\par
A software application for retrieving, presenting and traversing information resources on the World Wide Web\par
\par
\b HTTP\b0\par
Stands for Hypertext Transfer Protocol. It is a protocol managed by the W3C to dictate the manner in which Web pages share data on the World Wide Web. We might recognize this from the start of many Web addresses.\par
\par
\b HTTPS\b0\par
Stands for Hypertext Transder Protocol Secure. It is the secure version of HTTP, the protocol over which data is sent between our browser and the Web site that we are connected to. It means all communications between our browser and the Web site are encrypted. Some examples of sites that use HTTPS include the W3C and Microsoft Web sites.\par
\par
\ul\b\fs28 Separating content from presentation\ulnone\b0\par
\fs22 Up until now, we have been discussing CSS's role within a Web site as the "presentation" component, but what is that and why is it so important?\par
\par
From the history of CSS, we learned why CSS came about, but the short answer is simply because HTML was never designed to describe the way a Web page was supposed to look. When we use HTML for what it was intended to do, describe content, it leaves space for CSS to properly control a page's visuals. This makes it very easy to update or add content without having to even touch the style.\par
\par
\b Some benefits of CSS:\b0\par

\pard{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-360\li720\sl240\slmult1 CSS has a host of specialized tools to give us powerful control over the look and feel of our web site, much more powerful than the tools provided by HTML\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Designers can style many HTML pages with a single CSS document for consistent look and feel across an entire Web page and less code to maintain\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Separation of content and presentation makes Web site maintenance much simpler as we can address updates in isolation\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Over time more and more devices have become internet-capable, and now there are so many different orientations in which our user can view our content. With CSS, we can specifically cater the style to each device to ensure an optimal experience\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Some users have specific presentation needs based on personal or technological limitations or preferences. Separating content from presentation allows these users the option to control how they view content\par
{\pntext\f1\'B7\tab}Before CSS visual elements were almost always achieved with static images, which can have a big affect on network performance. CSS provides an optimized way to style our page so it can load complex visuals quickly.\par

